Yes, obviously a VP does not have authority to reject votes or exercise discretion, but Pence fails to address the constitutional option under Article II and 3 USC 15: because a final adjudication of claims had not occurred, he should have asked the state legislatures if the certifications presented were correct according to law.

This was a moment in American history that could have cemented state legislatures as the authority they are under Article II, Sec 1.2 for the manner of selecting electoral delegates. A lawless, runaway executive and a spineless state legislature is not what our founders intended.

Requiring the state legislatures to go on record to Congress would have forced a weak Republican leadership to confront the irredeemably compromised issues in the administration of the 2020 election and made them more obviously accountable for what they let happen.

Ultimately, if the state legislatures certified a Biden slate, we would be in the same position we are now, but with the nation knowing it’s the state legislatures who are ultimately responsible. Or, they could have certified the truth: the election was irredeemably compromised.

If they had certified the truth, they could have reclaimed their delegates and chosen to represent the will of their constituents, or certified to Congress there was no clearly adjudicated winner so neither Trump or Biden reached 270 and the House would have voted by delegation.

The electoral college is a brilliant process to select a president and has built-in fail safes. The only thing the founders didn’t anticipate was how weak future politicians would be instead of statesmen who are willing to pledge their lives, fortunes, and sacred honor to defend America’s integrity.
